      "The bell above the shop door had not rung in three days, which was how Samuel knew the town had finally forgotten about him, just as his grandfather had warned he would be forgotten.",
      "Rows of clocks lined the workshop walls, each keeping a slightly different time, their ticking overlapping into a soft, uneven rhythm that Samuel had once found comforting and now found merely loud.",
      "His grandfather used to say that a clockmaker's real skill was not fixing gears but noticing what customers never said aloud: the woman who wanted her late husband's watch running again, the boy who wanted a clock loud enough to drown out an empty house.",
      "Samuel had inherited the tools easily enough. The noticing, it turned out, was harder to inherit, and lately his workshop had begun to feel like a museum of a skill he had not quite learned in time.",
      "Then, on the fourth day, the bell rang. An old woman stood in the doorway holding a cracked pocket watch, and before she had said a single word, Samuel found himself asking not what was broken, but who it had once belonged to.",
