    id: "passage-allotment-key",
    title: "The Allotment Key",
    source: "original",
    paragraphs: [
      "Dev had dug the same corner of Plot 14 every Saturday since he was six, but he had never once struck metal. The spade rang out with a dull clank, and when he knelt to brush away the soil, he found the corner of a wooden box, its lid swollen shut and streaked green with age. His grandfather's allotment sat at the far edge of the site, tucked behind a hedge so overgrown that most other plot-holders had forgotten it existed. Dev worked the box free with both hands, surprised by how heavy it felt for something so small, and set it carefully on the path beside the runner beans his grandfather had planted every spring for as long as Dev could remember.",
      "The allotment had belonged to Grandad Arthur since before Dev's mother was born, and Arthur still talked about it as though it were the most important place in the world. He had once explained that the site had first been dug during the war, when every family on the street had been given a strip of land and told to grow whatever they could. Most of that history had faded into rumour, repeated at family dinners until nobody was sure which parts were true. Lately, though, Arthur had not been well enough to visit the plot himself, and Dev's mother checked her phone anxiously every time it buzzed, in case the hospital was calling with news neither of them wanted to hear.",
      "Dev turned the box over, looking for a way in, and found a small brass lock beneath a hinge stiff with rust. He remembered a key hanging on a nail inside Grandad's shed, ordinary and unlabelled, the kind of key nobody bothers to notice until it matters. Arthur had once mentioned, half-laughing, that the allotment committee used to guard a 'proper secret' from the war years, though he always changed the subject before finishing the story. Dev had assumed it was one of his grandfather's exaggerations, the kind told to make an ordinary vegetable patch sound thrilling. Now, crouched beside a box that clearly had not been opened in decades, he was no longer so certain.",
      "The shed key turned out to be too large for the lock, so Dev carried the box to Mrs Okafor, who tended the plot next door and had lived on the site for nearly as long as Arthur had. She examined the lock closely and disappeared into her own shed, returning with a small tin of assorted keys collected, she said, from allotment-holders who had long since moved away. Ten attempts later, a slim iron key clicked home and the lid released with a groan. Mrs Okafor stepped back politely, insisting that whatever lay inside belonged to Arthur's family alone to discover, though her curiosity was written plainly across her face.",
      "Inside, wrapped in oiled cloth to keep out the damp, Dev found a set of hand-drawn plans showing the whole allotment site divided into numbered strips, several tins of seeds far older than any he recognised, and a folded letter addressed simply to 'Whoever digs this up next.' The letter described how the plot-holders of 1943 had buried a box on every strip as a message to the future, each containing whatever they most wanted the next generation to know about growing things through difficult times. Arthur's strip, the letter explained, had been planted by his own grandfather, which meant the box had waited patiently through three generations for someone to finally notice it.",
      "Dev photographed everything carefully before cycling straight to the hospital, the box balanced on his handlebars the whole way. Arthur's face, tired and pale against the pillow, brightened the moment he saw the plans spread across the blanket. He traced the numbered strips with one finger, naming neighbours who had died years before Dev was born, and finally admitted that the 'proper secret' had been entirely true after all. For the first time in weeks, he asked Dev to describe exactly how the runner beans were coming along, and Dev realised that some stories only become believable once they are finally, physically, held in your hands.",
    ],
